1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,640
INSTRUCTOR: We'll now begin
part two of the lecture,

2
00:00:03,640 --> 00:00:09,360
identifying patients who benefit
from treatment using IAI applied

3
00:00:09,360 --> 00:00:13,320
to transformed real-world data.

4
00:00:13,320 --> 00:00:16,160
Let's begin with a
natural question.

5
00:00:16,160 --> 00:00:19,160
Why can't we simply use
the road one framework

6
00:00:19,160 --> 00:00:22,280
that I just presented
to identify patients who

7
00:00:22,280 --> 00:00:24,000
will benefit from treatment?

8
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:26,560
After all, we
already transformed

9
00:00:26,560 --> 00:00:30,840
the real-world data, corrected
for observed and unobserved

10
00:00:30,840 --> 00:00:34,360
confounding, and even
used interpretable

11
00:00:34,360 --> 00:00:37,400
AI to build actionable
decision rules

12
00:00:37,400 --> 00:00:39,760
and achieve precision medicine.

13
00:00:39,760 --> 00:00:42,400
So what is missing?

14
00:00:42,400 --> 00:00:46,440
The answer lies in understanding
the limitations of the road one

15
00:00:46,440 --> 00:00:50,440
framework, what it can
do, and more importantly,

16
00:00:50,440 --> 00:00:52,000
what it cannot.

17
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:53,800
Let me explain.

18
00:00:53,800 --> 00:00:58,640
Road one is effective when we
can tune for high sensitivity,

19
00:00:58,640 --> 00:01:01,970
and that makes sense
in two key scenarios.

20
00:01:01,970 --> 00:01:05,129
First, when we can
justify assigning

21
00:01:05,129 --> 00:01:07,930
a large weight because
the treatment benefit

22
00:01:07,930 --> 00:01:10,730
is known to be strong.

23
00:01:10,730 --> 00:01:13,890
This is a classic
landmark RCT scenario

24
00:01:13,890 --> 00:01:19,730
where clear trial data show that
treatment prevents bad outcomes.

25
00:01:19,730 --> 00:01:24,090
Here, road one helps us
safely identify patients

26
00:01:24,090 --> 00:01:27,130
who don't need the treatment
because the treatment works

27
00:01:27,130 --> 00:01:30,850
and missing a true
responder would be costly.

28
00:01:30,850 --> 00:01:36,050
Second, even if the treatments
benefit is modest or uncertain,

29
00:01:36,050 --> 00:01:38,170
we might still
assign a large weight

30
00:01:38,170 --> 00:01:42,770
to preserve high sensitivity,
especially in practice settings

31
00:01:42,770 --> 00:01:46,610
where the treatment
is used by default.

32
00:01:46,610 --> 00:01:48,970
Take, for example,
adjuvant chemotherapy

33
00:01:48,970 --> 00:01:52,090
for colorectal cancer
liver metastasis.

34
00:01:52,090 --> 00:01:56,850
Despite multiple RCTs, the
benefit remains inconclusive.

35
00:01:56,850 --> 00:02:01,660
Yet, many centers routinely
offer it just in case

36
00:02:01,660 --> 00:02:03,420
it helps someone.

37
00:02:03,420 --> 00:02:06,540
So the clinical
goal becomes can we

38
00:02:06,540 --> 00:02:10,940
identify patients who clearly do
not need chemotherapy and spare

39
00:02:10,940 --> 00:02:15,220
them the toxicity of a treatment
they won't benefit from?

40
00:02:15,220 --> 00:02:17,540
In both of these
cases, high sensitivity

41
00:02:17,540 --> 00:02:20,660
helps us focus on
safety by making

42
00:02:20,660 --> 00:02:25,580
sure we don't miss patients
who might actually benefit.

43
00:02:25,580 --> 00:02:29,220
But now, consider a
very different question.

44
00:02:29,220 --> 00:02:32,900
What if our goal is to identify
patients who will actually

45
00:02:32,900 --> 00:02:35,220
benefit from treatment?

46
00:02:35,220 --> 00:02:37,620
Not just those
who might need it,

47
00:02:37,620 --> 00:02:41,420
not just those who are
high risk, but those

48
00:02:41,420 --> 00:02:44,580
who truly improve with therapy.

49
00:02:44,580 --> 00:02:48,060
Think of these patients
with an exon mutation.

50
00:02:48,060 --> 00:02:52,420
They are at high risk, but they
respond poorly to imatinib.

51
00:02:52,420 --> 00:02:57,790
In that case, need and
benefit are not the same.

52
00:02:57,790 --> 00:02:59,470
So here's the problem.

53
00:02:59,470 --> 00:03:02,870
If we blindly tune
for high sensitivity,

54
00:03:02,870 --> 00:03:06,030
we might still assign
treatment to high-risk patients

55
00:03:06,030 --> 00:03:09,030
who don't benefit at all.

56
00:03:09,030 --> 00:03:11,710
That's why the metrics
we used before,

57
00:03:11,710 --> 00:03:14,350
like sensitivity to
tune the weights,

58
00:03:14,350 --> 00:03:18,750
break down when the goal is no
longer to avoid undertreatment,

59
00:03:18,750 --> 00:03:23,910
but to pinpoint who
actually gains from therapy.

60
00:03:23,910 --> 00:03:27,510
In those cases, we need
a different approach.

61
00:03:27,510 --> 00:03:32,390
And that's what we
will explore next.

62
00:03:32,390 --> 00:03:35,630
So how should we
tune the weights

63
00:03:35,630 --> 00:03:38,830
to address unobserved
confounding when our goal is

64
00:03:38,830 --> 00:03:43,030
to identify treatment benefit?

65
00:03:43,030 --> 00:03:45,710
The key idea is
this, use a target

66
00:03:45,710 --> 00:03:49,510
RCT to guide the weight tuning.

67
00:03:49,510 --> 00:03:52,550
By target RCT, I mean
a randomized trial

68
00:03:52,550 --> 00:03:57,090
that was conducted in a cohort
similar to our real-world data

69
00:03:57,090 --> 00:03:58,610
set.

70
00:03:58,610 --> 00:04:01,330
Let's walk through an example.

71
00:04:01,330 --> 00:04:07,170
Suppose we complete step one
of road one in an RWD cohort.

72
00:04:07,170 --> 00:04:10,510
We observe that a five-year
Recurrence-Free Survival,

73
00:04:10,510 --> 00:04:15,290
or RFS, is 39% in
the untreated group

74
00:04:15,290 --> 00:04:18,170
and 40% in the treated group.

75
00:04:18,170 --> 00:04:20,970
That's basically no difference.

76
00:04:20,970 --> 00:04:24,970
But now, we bring in
external knowledge.

77
00:04:24,970 --> 00:04:30,170
In RCT, in a similar population
reports a true treatment effect

78
00:04:30,170 --> 00:04:34,330
corresponding to a
hazard ratio of 0.5.

79
00:04:34,330 --> 00:04:36,530
That's a strong signal.

80
00:04:36,530 --> 00:04:40,010
If we convert that
into five-year RFS

81
00:04:40,010 --> 00:04:43,610
using a Cox proportional
hazards model,

82
00:04:43,610 --> 00:04:49,690
it implies that treated patients
in our RWD should have about 62%

83
00:04:49,690 --> 00:04:52,170
survival at five years.

84
00:04:52,170 --> 00:04:55,100
So what can we do with that?

85
00:04:55,100 --> 00:05:00,340
We can use this RCT
benchmark to guide our model.

86
00:05:00,340 --> 00:05:02,700
We increase the weight
of treated patients

87
00:05:02,700 --> 00:05:06,660
with good outcomes, those who
received treatment ended well,

88
00:05:06,660 --> 00:05:11,540
until our real-world model
starts to recover that 62% are

89
00:05:11,540 --> 00:05:16,140
RFS, matching what the RCT
observed for the treatment

90
00:05:16,140 --> 00:05:18,140
group.

91
00:05:18,140 --> 00:05:21,420
It's a practical way to tune
the model toward the true effect

92
00:05:21,420 --> 00:05:22,860
size.

93
00:05:22,860 --> 00:05:24,900
Sounds simple, right?

94
00:05:24,900 --> 00:05:28,700
But there is a critical caveat.

95
00:05:28,700 --> 00:05:31,740
We have to be sure
the RCT's treatment

96
00:05:31,740 --> 00:05:36,500
effect is transportable
to our real-world cohort.

97
00:05:36,500 --> 00:05:40,420
That is, we can't just
import results from a trial

98
00:05:40,420 --> 00:05:43,300
and expect them to
apply automatically.

99
00:05:43,300 --> 00:05:48,100
To do this validly, we must
ensure that our real-world data

100
00:05:48,100 --> 00:05:51,100
is prognostically similar
to the RCT cohort,

101
00:05:51,100 --> 00:05:55,390
with the exception, of course,
of unobserved confounding, which

102
00:05:55,390 --> 00:05:57,020
the weights are
meant to address.

103
00:05:57,020 --> 00:05:59,670


104
00:05:59,670 --> 00:06:02,150
Let's now revisit
what this methodology

105
00:06:02,150 --> 00:06:05,470
looks like in
practice, specifically,

106
00:06:05,470 --> 00:06:11,510
how chapter 2 of the road
framework builds on chapter 1.

107
00:06:11,510 --> 00:06:14,430
Start on the left
side of the slide.

108
00:06:14,430 --> 00:06:17,310
In road one we performed
prognostic matching

109
00:06:17,310 --> 00:06:20,470
within buckets of baseline risk.

110
00:06:20,470 --> 00:06:25,430
This risk was estimated using
a counterfactual model trained

111
00:06:25,430 --> 00:06:27,750
only on the untreated patients.

112
00:06:27,750 --> 00:06:32,710
Now, in road two, we
take that logic further

113
00:06:32,710 --> 00:06:38,390
and we explicitly emulate the
target RCT in multiple ways.

114
00:06:38,390 --> 00:06:40,830
The additions are
shown in red font

115
00:06:40,830 --> 00:06:43,350
on the right side of the slide.

116
00:06:43,350 --> 00:06:46,750
So what exactly do we add?

117
00:06:46,750 --> 00:06:51,480
Step 1, we apply the eligibility
criteria of the target RCT

118
00:06:51,480 --> 00:06:55,080
to the real-world data.

119
00:06:55,080 --> 00:06:59,400
This ensures we're comparing
similar populations.

120
00:06:59,400 --> 00:07:03,240
Step 2, we still perform
prognostic matching

121
00:07:03,240 --> 00:07:05,580
between treated and
untreated patients,

122
00:07:05,580 --> 00:07:08,840
but now we do two more things.

123
00:07:08,840 --> 00:07:13,880
First, we align the baseline
prognosis of the RWD untreated

124
00:07:13,880 --> 00:07:18,920
and treated groups with that of
the placebo group in the trial.

125
00:07:18,920 --> 00:07:20,120
Why?

126
00:07:20,120 --> 00:07:23,240
Because, in an RCT,
the placebo group

127
00:07:23,240 --> 00:07:27,320
defines the baseline prognosis.

128
00:07:27,320 --> 00:07:31,720
The only difference between
the placebo and treatment arms

129
00:07:31,720 --> 00:07:34,640
is the treatment itself.

130
00:07:34,640 --> 00:07:37,840
So if we want to recover
the treatment effect seen

131
00:07:37,840 --> 00:07:41,600
in the RCT, we need to make
sure the baseline prognosis

132
00:07:41,600 --> 00:07:45,080
of our real-world
patients mirrors that

133
00:07:45,080 --> 00:07:48,880
of the trial placebo group.

134
00:07:48,880 --> 00:07:52,290
Second, we align the
marginal distribution

135
00:07:52,290 --> 00:07:54,770
of important
prognostic variables,

136
00:07:54,770 --> 00:07:58,930
such as KRAS mutational
status or tumor sidedness,

137
00:07:58,930 --> 00:08:00,890
with the trial.

138
00:08:00,890 --> 00:08:04,130
This matters because
baseline prognosis can

139
00:08:04,130 --> 00:08:07,410
be formed in different ways.

140
00:08:07,410 --> 00:08:10,570
A predicted survival
of 50% could

141
00:08:10,570 --> 00:08:13,970
reflect a mix of very
high and very low-risk

142
00:08:13,970 --> 00:08:20,610
patients, or a homogeneous
group all hovering around 50%.

143
00:08:20,610 --> 00:08:23,270
Matching the marginal
covariate distributions,

144
00:08:23,270 --> 00:08:25,690
especially that of
treatment modifiers,

145
00:08:25,690 --> 00:08:30,490
helps us preserve the
structure of the RCT.

146
00:08:30,490 --> 00:08:33,330
By doing both of these,
aligning prognosis

147
00:08:33,330 --> 00:08:37,650
and covariate distributions,
we make an assumption

148
00:08:37,650 --> 00:08:42,370
that this dual alignment also
brings the joint distribution

149
00:08:42,370 --> 00:08:48,620
of prognostic factors in the
RWD close to that in the RCT.

150
00:08:48,620 --> 00:08:51,340
Only after this
careful alignment

151
00:08:51,340 --> 00:08:56,420
do we proceed to step
3, tuning the weights

152
00:08:56,420 --> 00:08:58,940
of treated patients
with good outcomes

153
00:08:58,940 --> 00:09:02,730
to reproduce the treatment
effect observed in the trial.

154
00:09:02,730 --> 00:09:05,740


155
00:09:05,740 --> 00:09:09,780
Let's now take a quick
look under the hood

156
00:09:09,780 --> 00:09:13,300
at the optimization framework
that powers the matching

157
00:09:13,300 --> 00:09:17,820
procedure in road chapter 2.

158
00:09:17,820 --> 00:09:19,920
This expression
may look complex,

159
00:09:19,920 --> 00:09:23,260
but the logic is
straightforward.

160
00:09:23,260 --> 00:09:26,060
The goal is to minimize
the total discrepancy

161
00:09:26,060 --> 00:09:29,460
between our real-world
cohort and the placebo

162
00:09:29,460 --> 00:09:35,140
arm of the target RCT along
several key dimensions.

163
00:09:35,140 --> 00:09:37,780
First, we estimate
baseline prognosis

164
00:09:37,780 --> 00:09:40,860
for each patient using our
counterfactual model which

165
00:09:40,860 --> 00:09:44,620
is trained exclusively on the
untreated real-world group.

166
00:09:44,620 --> 00:09:48,370
We then apply this model
to both treated patients,

167
00:09:48,370 --> 00:09:52,590
denoted i, and untreated
patients, denoted j,

168
00:09:52,590 --> 00:09:55,390
in the real-world data.

169
00:09:55,390 --> 00:09:59,390
Next, we minimize the difference
between the predicted baseline

170
00:09:59,390 --> 00:10:03,190
prognosis for these
two real-world groups

171
00:10:03,190 --> 00:10:08,110
and the actual recurrence risk
observed in the RCT's placebo

172
00:10:08,110 --> 00:10:09,790
arm.

173
00:10:09,790 --> 00:10:13,990
Second, we simultaneously
match on marginal covariate

174
00:10:13,990 --> 00:10:17,670
distributions, ensuring
that prognostic variables

175
00:10:17,670 --> 00:10:19,830
like KRAS status
or tumor location

176
00:10:19,830 --> 00:10:24,390
are represented in the same
proportions in each RWD group

177
00:10:24,390 --> 00:10:27,710
as in the trial population.

178
00:10:27,710 --> 00:10:31,470
Third, we preserve within
bucket prognostic balance,

179
00:10:31,470 --> 00:10:33,590
just as we did in road one.

180
00:10:33,590 --> 00:10:38,510
This ensures a fair comparison
of treated and untreated RWD

181
00:10:38,510 --> 00:10:40,270
patients.

182
00:10:40,270 --> 00:10:44,030
In simple terms, we are solving
a multi-objective matching

183
00:10:44,030 --> 00:10:47,570
problem balancing
baseline prognosis,

184
00:10:47,570 --> 00:10:52,250
covariate distributions,
and internal consistency.

185
00:10:52,250 --> 00:10:56,090
This allows us to build
a real-world cohort that

186
00:10:56,090 --> 00:11:00,730
mirrors the trial population in
both structure and prognosis,

187
00:11:00,730 --> 00:11:04,210
which is the foundation we need
before we tune for treatment

188
00:11:04,210 --> 00:11:04,710
effect.

189
00:11:04,710 --> 00:11:07,890


190
00:11:07,890 --> 00:11:10,970
After completing the two
core transformation steps

191
00:11:10,970 --> 00:11:13,930
we just discussed,
we trained our model

192
00:11:13,930 --> 00:11:16,570
using real-world
data from patients

193
00:11:16,570 --> 00:11:19,370
with colorectal cancer
liver metastasis,

194
00:11:19,370 --> 00:11:22,610
including cohorts from Johns
Hopkins, Cleveland Clinic,

195
00:11:22,610 --> 00:11:26,690
Stanford and other
collaborators.

196
00:11:26,690 --> 00:11:29,210
For external validation,
we used a published

197
00:11:29,210 --> 00:11:35,010
randomized controlled trial,
which appeared in JCO in 2021.

198
00:11:35,010 --> 00:11:38,010
Here is how we
validated the framework.

199
00:11:38,010 --> 00:11:40,970
First, we use our
real-world data

200
00:11:40,970 --> 00:11:43,490
to train optimal
policy trees which

201
00:11:43,490 --> 00:11:45,820
defined subgroups of
patients predicted

202
00:11:45,820 --> 00:11:48,860
to benefit from chemotherapy.

203
00:11:48,860 --> 00:11:51,540
Then we generated
Kaplan-Meier plots

204
00:11:51,540 --> 00:11:56,460
showing actual outcomes within
each of those subgroups.

205
00:11:56,460 --> 00:12:00,220
Next, we reached out to the team
at the National Cancer Center

206
00:12:00,220 --> 00:12:06,100
Hospital in Tokyo, the authors
of the JCO 0603 trial and asked

207
00:12:06,100 --> 00:12:08,180
them to generate the
Kaplan-Meier plots

208
00:12:08,180 --> 00:12:14,860
for our subgroups, but this
time using their RCT data.

209
00:12:14,860 --> 00:12:16,980
This gave us a
unique opportunity

210
00:12:16,980 --> 00:12:22,180
to compare side by side how
the OPT subgroups performed

211
00:12:22,180 --> 00:12:26,860
in real-world versus
trial settings.

212
00:12:26,860 --> 00:12:30,740
We validated our approach
across three levels.

213
00:12:30,740 --> 00:12:34,780
First, direction of benefit.

214
00:12:34,780 --> 00:12:37,220
Did the chemotherapy
subgroup show improvement

215
00:12:37,220 --> 00:12:40,020
in both data sets?

216
00:12:40,020 --> 00:12:43,470
Second level,
statistical significance.

217
00:12:43,470 --> 00:12:48,390
Was the benefit statistically
significant in both data sets?

218
00:12:48,390 --> 00:12:52,190
And the third level,
magnitude of benefit.

219
00:12:52,190 --> 00:12:55,530
Was the improvement in median
recurrence-free survival

220
00:12:55,530 --> 00:12:58,550
similar in both data sets?

221
00:12:58,550 --> 00:13:00,830
If all three
criteria aligned, we

222
00:13:00,830 --> 00:13:06,750
consider the OPT subgroup
successfully validated.

223
00:13:06,750 --> 00:13:09,830
Let's now look at the results
for the first optimal policy

224
00:13:09,830 --> 00:13:11,830
tree.

225
00:13:11,830 --> 00:13:14,190
In the panels on
the upper right,

226
00:13:14,190 --> 00:13:19,070
we grouped together patients
who, according to the first OPT,

227
00:13:19,070 --> 00:13:23,350
should receive
adjuvant chemotherapy.

228
00:13:23,350 --> 00:13:27,830
Panel A shows outcomes in our
real-world emulated cohort,

229
00:13:27,830 --> 00:13:32,030
and panel B shows outcomes
in the RCT cohort.

230
00:13:32,030 --> 00:13:36,630
As you can see, the Kaplan-Meier
curves are visually aligned.

231
00:13:36,630 --> 00:13:39,830
And more importantly, the
benefit from chemotherapy

232
00:13:39,830 --> 00:13:44,120
is statistically significant
in both data sets.

233
00:13:44,120 --> 00:13:48,280
Even more impressive is the
consistency in magnitude.

234
00:13:48,280 --> 00:13:50,990
Median recurrence-free
survival improved from 11

235
00:13:50,990 --> 00:13:54,320
to 33 months in the
real-world cohort,

236
00:13:54,320 --> 00:13:58,800
and from 17 to 41 months
in the RCT cohort.

237
00:13:58,800 --> 00:14:02,560
This is a striking example
of transportability.

238
00:14:02,560 --> 00:14:06,120
A subgroup identified
from real-world data

239
00:14:06,120 --> 00:14:09,800
showed consistent benefit
when applied to an RCT data

240
00:14:09,800 --> 00:14:13,920
set who had no prior access to.

241
00:14:13,920 --> 00:14:18,000
Now look at the lower
right side of the slide.

242
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:22,400
Here, we grouped patients who
the first OPT predicted would

243
00:14:22,400 --> 00:14:25,040
not benefit from chemotherapy.

244
00:14:25,040 --> 00:14:28,560
Again, panel A is
from our RWD cohort,

245
00:14:28,560 --> 00:14:31,920
and panel B is from the RCT.

246
00:14:31,920 --> 00:14:35,800
As you can see, there is no
clear benefit from chemotherapy

247
00:14:35,800 --> 00:14:38,120
in either cohort.

248
00:14:38,120 --> 00:14:40,440
The curves are
almost overlapping

249
00:14:40,440 --> 00:14:44,250
and the p values
are non-significant.

250
00:14:44,250 --> 00:14:47,690
These results support
two key conclusions.

251
00:14:47,690 --> 00:14:53,490
First, the OPT correctly
identifies treatment responders,

252
00:14:53,490 --> 00:14:57,490
and just as importantly,
it can identify subgroups

253
00:14:57,490 --> 00:15:00,290
with no meaningful
benefit, helping

254
00:15:00,290 --> 00:15:04,450
us avoid unnecessary treatment.

255
00:15:04,450 --> 00:15:06,730
What makes this
especially powerful

256
00:15:06,730 --> 00:15:08,890
is the external validation.

257
00:15:08,890 --> 00:15:12,850
The subgroups were defined
using real-world data performed

258
00:15:12,850 --> 00:15:16,690
similarly in the RCT,
which we had no access to

259
00:15:16,690 --> 00:15:20,250
during development.

260
00:15:20,250 --> 00:15:24,130
Let's now turn to the
second optimal policy tree.

261
00:15:24,130 --> 00:15:27,890
We followed the exact
same validation process.

262
00:15:27,890 --> 00:15:31,130
On the upper right, you
see the Kaplan-Meier plots

263
00:15:31,130 --> 00:15:34,090
for patients who, according
to the second OPT,

264
00:15:34,090 --> 00:15:38,770
were recommended to receive
adjuvant chemotherapy.

265
00:15:38,770 --> 00:15:42,180
Panel A shows the
real-world cohort,

266
00:15:42,180 --> 00:15:45,420
and panel B shows
the RCT cohort.

267
00:15:45,420 --> 00:15:48,140
Once again, the
treatment effect is

268
00:15:48,140 --> 00:15:51,740
visually and statistically
consistent across both data

269
00:15:51,740 --> 00:15:53,620
sets.

270
00:15:53,620 --> 00:15:55,920
The benefit is
statistically significant

271
00:15:55,920 --> 00:16:01,300
and the magnitude of benefit
is nearly identical, 10 versus

272
00:16:01,300 --> 00:16:05,620
32 months in the real-world
cohort and 16 versus 36

273
00:16:05,620 --> 00:16:09,140
months in the RCT cohort.

274
00:16:09,140 --> 00:16:12,900
On the lower right, we focus
on patients who the OPT advised

275
00:16:12,900 --> 00:16:15,420
against chemotherapy.

276
00:16:15,420 --> 00:16:20,020
In both the real-world and RCT
cohorts, there is no benefit.

277
00:16:20,020 --> 00:16:22,340
The Kaplan-Meier
curves are overlapping

278
00:16:22,340 --> 00:16:25,060
and the p values
are not significant.

279
00:16:25,060 --> 00:16:29,540
This reinforces our
earlier findings, first,

280
00:16:29,540 --> 00:16:31,740
that the model
successfully identifies

281
00:16:31,740 --> 00:16:35,180
subgroups who benefit,
and just as importantly,

282
00:16:35,180 --> 00:16:38,550
it identifies subgroups
who don't, helping

283
00:16:38,550 --> 00:16:40,910
us avoid unnecessary treatment.

284
00:16:40,910 --> 00:16:43,710
And again, these
findings were externally

285
00:16:43,710 --> 00:16:47,070
validated in an
independent RCT cohort

286
00:16:47,070 --> 00:16:53,070
that was entirely separate
from model development.

287
00:16:53,070 --> 00:16:57,670
To summarize, in part 2,
we addressed the question,

288
00:16:57,670 --> 00:17:01,590
how can we identify patients
who truly benefit from treatment

289
00:17:01,590 --> 00:17:04,750
using real-world data?

290
00:17:04,750 --> 00:17:08,829
This led to four
key innovations.

291
00:17:08,829 --> 00:17:12,950
First, we introduced a novel
prognostic matching technique

292
00:17:12,950 --> 00:17:16,589
that extracts a cohort
from observational data

293
00:17:16,589 --> 00:17:19,910
and aligns both patient
characteristics and baseline

294
00:17:19,910 --> 00:17:25,630
prognosis with those of the
placebo group in a target RCT.

295
00:17:25,630 --> 00:17:29,470
Second, we developed a
new weight-tuning method

296
00:17:29,470 --> 00:17:31,950
to address unobserved
confounding

297
00:17:31,950 --> 00:17:34,470
by aligning the
post-treatment prognosis

298
00:17:34,470 --> 00:17:37,730
in the real-world
treated group with that

299
00:17:37,730 --> 00:17:42,690
observed in the treated
group of the target RCT.

300
00:17:42,690 --> 00:17:45,210
Third, we demonstrated
the ability

301
00:17:45,210 --> 00:17:48,450
to identify subgroups with
varying levels of treatment

302
00:17:48,450 --> 00:17:53,410
benefit, including those who
receive no benefit at all.

303
00:17:53,410 --> 00:17:56,730
And fourth, we
validated this framework

304
00:17:56,730 --> 00:17:59,830
using a completely
independent RCT data

305
00:17:59,830 --> 00:18:03,090
set, one who had
no prior access to,

306
00:18:03,090 --> 00:18:09,250
ensuring truly unbiased
external validation.

307
00:18:09,250 --> 00:18:11,370
In contrast to part
one of the lecture,

308
00:18:11,370 --> 00:18:16,450
road 2 requires the
existence of a relevant RCT

309
00:18:16,450 --> 00:18:21,170
because you use the trials
results to inform the weights.

310
00:18:21,170 --> 00:18:24,130
So a natural question arises.

311
00:18:24,130 --> 00:18:28,850
Why go through the trouble of
debiasing real-world data if we

312
00:18:28,850 --> 00:18:30,730
already have RCT?

313
00:18:30,730 --> 00:18:34,650
Why not just train
optimal policy trees

314
00:18:34,650 --> 00:18:38,780
directly on the trial data?

315
00:18:38,780 --> 00:18:43,540
At first glance, this might
seem like the simpler path,

316
00:18:43,540 --> 00:18:48,020
but training OPTs on the
biased real-world data

317
00:18:48,020 --> 00:18:51,580
has several key advantages.

318
00:18:51,580 --> 00:18:56,620
First, real world data
is much more abundant.

319
00:18:56,620 --> 00:19:01,220
This abundance allows us to
emulate trials at larger sample

320
00:19:01,220 --> 00:19:08,140
sizes, solving a major issue
in RCTs, low statistical power.

321
00:19:08,140 --> 00:19:11,860
RCTs are often underpowered
because of cost and time

322
00:19:11,860 --> 00:19:14,300
limitations.

323
00:19:14,300 --> 00:19:16,380
This becomes even
more problematic

324
00:19:16,380 --> 00:19:18,940
when doing subgroup
analysis, like we

325
00:19:18,940 --> 00:19:21,340
do with OPTs, which
carve the data set

326
00:19:21,340 --> 00:19:24,620
into smaller and
smaller groups, further

327
00:19:24,620 --> 00:19:28,820
reducing power and precision.

328
00:19:28,820 --> 00:19:31,820
Second, RWD can
include variables

329
00:19:31,820 --> 00:19:34,910
that original RCTs
don't capture.

330
00:19:34,910 --> 00:19:38,710
For example, genomics
and other omics data

331
00:19:38,710 --> 00:19:42,150
are increasingly
available in RWD,

332
00:19:42,150 --> 00:19:46,670
but are often missing
from older trials.

333
00:19:46,670 --> 00:19:49,110
This data can be
biologically meaningful

334
00:19:49,110 --> 00:19:52,470
and add a richer layer
of interpretation.

335
00:19:52,470 --> 00:19:57,950
Importantly, because omics
reflect intrinsic biology,

336
00:19:57,950 --> 00:20:00,710
their distributions are
more likely to be consistent

337
00:20:00,710 --> 00:20:04,270
across data sets, making
them reliable inputs

338
00:20:04,270 --> 00:20:08,350
when aligning RWD to an RCT.

339
00:20:08,350 --> 00:20:12,110
Third, this approach
enables broader access

340
00:20:12,110 --> 00:20:14,030
and faster analysis.

341
00:20:14,030 --> 00:20:17,150
Most RCT data sets
are proprietary,

342
00:20:17,150 --> 00:20:22,910
held by academic groups or
sponsors, but with debiased RWD,

343
00:20:22,910 --> 00:20:27,750
multiple teams can work on a
common emulated trial data set.

344
00:20:27,750 --> 00:20:31,390
This democratizes
precision medicine research

345
00:20:31,390 --> 00:20:34,720
and accelerates discovery.